map_nz1 = map_nz +
  tm_shape(nz_elev) + tm_raster(alpha = 0.8)

map_nz1

as many layers or shapes as possible can be added to tmap objects. st_buffer computes a buffer around this geometry/each geometry st_union Combines several feature geometries into one, without unioning or resolving internal boundaries st_cast - Casts/Converts one geometry to another type: either simplify, or cast explicitly we can convert to MULTIPOLYGON, POINT, LINESTRING, etc.

we indicate New Zealands Territorial Waters by creating a layer as defined by the 1982 United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea,[1] is a belt of coastal waters extending at 12 nautical miles (22.2 km) source: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Territorial_waters

nz_water = st_union(nz) %>% st_buffer(22200) %>% 
  st_cast(to = "LINESTRING")

merge the Territorial waters layer with the Original NZ map

map_nz2 = map_nz1 +
  tm_shape(nz_water) + tm_lines()

#view

add nz_height layer

map_nz3 = map_nz2 +
  tm_shape(nz_height) + tm_dots()

#view
map_nz3

Plot all our created maps previously tmap_arrange()

tmap_arrange(map_nz1, map_nz2, map_nz3)

Coordinate Reference Systems (CRS) - Projections

If a projection is not explicitly defined in the first call to tm_shape, then the output map will default to the first layers reference system. crs values -> 4326 3857 +proj=robin . +proj=longlat there are 3 main types (Source: Geocomputation with R)

to view the different projection attributes

crs_data = rgdal::make_EPSG()
View(crs_data)

select the best projection attribute

tm_shape(World[136,], projection=4326) + 
  tm_polygons() + 
  tm_layout("Long lat coordinates", inner.margins=c(0,0,.1,0), title.size=.8)

we can also use dplyr to query one particular country or the traditional method ( country: Russia projection: +proj=stere +lat_0=90 +lat_ts=90 +lon_0=105 +k=0.994 +x_0=2000000 +y_0=2000000 +datum=WGS84 +units=m +no_defs

map_ru = tm_shape(World[World$name=="Russia", ], projection = "+proj=stere +lat_0=90 +lat_ts=90 +lon_0=105 +k=0.994 +x_0=2000000 +y_0=2000000 +datum=WGS84 +units=m +no_defs
") +
  tm_polygons()

add another layer to the previous map

map_ru + 
  tm_compass(type = "8star", position = c("left", "top")) +
  tm_scale_bar(breaks = c(0, 100, 200), text.size = 1)

we can also switch the map mode to view

tmap_mode("view")
## tmap mode set to interactive viewing
map_ru + tm_basemap(server="OpenStreetMap",alpha=0.5)

swtich back to plot mode

tmap_mode("plot")
## tmap mode set to plotting

we can also plot various map styles

map_ru + tm_style("bw")

map_ru + tm_style("classic")

map_ru + tm_style("cobalt")

map_ru + tm_style("col_blind")

working with the russian map, lets add the metro dataset and plot the projected population for 2020

map_ru + tm_style("col_blind") +
  tm_shape(metro) +
  tm_bubbles("pop2020")

Bounding Box

we can also use the bbox parameter to focus on a particular country

tm_shape(World, bbox = "Russia", projection = 4326) +
  tm_polygons("MAP_COLORS", palette="Pastel2") + 
  tm_shape(metro) +
  tm_bubbles("pop2010", title.size = "Population")

tm_shape(World, bbox = "Russia", projection = "+proj=longlat") +
  tm_fill() +
  tm_borders()+
  tm_shape(rivers) +
  tm_lines(col="dodgerblue3")
